Reductive stress on life span extension in C. elegans.

Ralser M(1), Benjamin IJ.

Author information:
(1)Max Planck Institute for Molecular Genetics, Ihnestrasse 73, 14195 Berlin, 
Germany. ralser@molgen.mpg.de

Recently, Schulz and colleagues have contributed to the ongoing controversy on 
the unproven role of oxidative stress in the aging process in their 
well-performed study 'Glucose restriction extends Caenorhabditis elegans life 
span by inducing mitochondrial respiration and increasing oxidative stress' 
(Cell Metab 2007, 6: 280-293). Here, we suggest an alternative hypothesis that 
reductive stress can prevent calorie-restriction induced life span extension. We 
draw attention to this condition as an explanation for some contradictory 
observations including the deleterious effects from antioxidants.

